==English==

===Etymology===
From earlier {{term|seise|lang=en}}, from {{etyl|enm}} {{term|seisen|lang=enm}}, {{term|seysen|lang=enm}}, {{term|sesen|lang=enm}}, {{term|ceesen|lang=enm}}, {{term|saisen|lang=enm}}, {{term|saysen|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|saisir|lang=fro}}, {{term|seisir|lang=enm||put one in possession of, take possessino of, seize}} (cf. modern French {{term|saisir||to seize|lang=fr}}), from Frankish {{etyl|la}} {{term|sacire|sacīre|take possession of, lay hold of, seize another's property|lang=la}} (8th century) in the phrase {{term||ad propriam sacire}}. Ultimately borrowed from some Germanic source; cf {{proto|Germanic|lang=|satjanan|to place}}, whence also English {{term|set|lang=en}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|sēz}}, {{IPA|/siːz/}}, {{SAMPA|/si:z/}}
* {{audio|en-us-seize.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{homophones|seas|sees}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|seiz|ing}}

# {{transitive}} to deliberately take hold of; to [[grab]] or [[capture]]
# {{transitive}} to take advantage of (an [[opportunity]] or [[circumstance]])
# {{transitive}} to take possession of (by force, law etc.)
#: ''to seize smuggled goods''
#: ''to seize a ship after libeling''
# {{transitive}} to have a sudden and powerful effect upon
#: ''a panic seized the crowd''
#: ''a fever seized him''
# {{transitive|Nautical}} to [[bind]], [[lash]] or make [[fast]], with several turns of small rope, cord, or small line
#: ''to seize two fish-hooks back to back''
#: ''to seize or stop one rope on to another''
# {{transitive|obsolete}} to [[fasten]], [[fix]]
# {{intransitive}} to lay hold in [[seizure]], by hands or claws (+ {{term|on|lang=en}} or {{term|upon|lang=en}})
#: ''to seize on the neck of a horse''
#: ''The text which had seized upon his heart with such comfort and strength abode upon him for more than a year.'' (''Southey'', Bunyan, p. 21)
# {{intransitive}} to have a [[seizure]]
# {{intransitive}} to [[bind]] or [[lock]] in position [[immovably]]; see also '''[[seize up]]'''
#: ''Rust caused the engine to '''seize''', never to run again.''

